signal_functions

1- void	void (*signal(int sig, void (*handler)(int)))(int)
- function returns a pointer to a function that takes an int as input
and returns a void

sig = the signal number
handler == a pointer to a function, could be:
void	handler(int signum) -> return value the previous signal
handler

example:

void my_handler(int signum) {
    printf("Caught %d\n", signum);
}

int main() {
    signal(SIGINT, my_handler);
    while (1);
}

a better alternative would be:

2- int	sigaction(int signum, const struct sigaction *act,
struct sigaction *oldact)

meaning:

signum = the signal number in question;
act = a pointer to a struct sigaction, that describes what i want
the new handler to be
oldact = if not NULL, the kernel fills this up with the previous
action for that signal

struct sigaction {
 void     (*sa_handler)(int); // simple signal handler
 void     (*sa_sigaction)(int, siginfo_t *, void *); // advanced handler
 sigset_t   sa_mask;	 // collection of signals to block while handler runs
 int        sa_flags;   // special flags controlling behavior
};

3- int	sigemptyset(sigset_t *set)
- this function initializes a signal set so that it contains no signals

so, if sigset_t is a bag of signals, sigemptyset() makes the bag empty

we could do:
struct sigaction sa;
sigemptyset(&sa.sa_mask); this means "while running the signal handler, do
not block any additional signals"

4- int	sigaddset(sigset_t *set, int signum)

adds a signal to a signal set, lets say signals are nodes in a list, this
function adds signals to it

so we use sigemptyset() to empty the bag and sigaddset() to add a specific
signal into it

so we could do the following:

struct sigaction sa;
sigemptyset(&sa.sa_mask);             // start with an empty set
sigaddset(&sa.sa_mask, SIGTERM);      // block SIGTERM while handler runs
sigaddset(&sa.sa_mask, SIGHUP);       // block SIGHUP while handler runs

so when the handling runs, the selected signals cant  interrupt it

5- int	kill(pid_t pid, int sig)
kill() sends a signal to a process or a group of processes

pid = identifies the target of the signal
if pid > 0 -> send the signal to process with that PID
if pid == 0 -> send signal to all processes in the same process group
as the caller
if pid < -1 -> send signal to all processes in the process group w id
abs(pid)
if pid == -1 -> send to all processes the caller has permission to signal

return values
0 → success

-1 → failure (check errno for reason,
e.g., EPERM for permission denied or ESRCH if process doesn’t exist)

to initialize the signal struct is important to set all the bytes of memory to 0
to avoid undefined behaviour





